{"title_page": "Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz (conductor)", "text_new": "'''Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz''' (28 August 1929{{spaced ndash}}16 April 1973) was an internationally acclaimed [[Jewish]] [[Hungary|Hungarian]] orchestral and operatic [[conducting|conductor]] who, throughout his brief but distinguished career led many of the world's great orchestras, including the Cleveland, Chicago, Philadelphia, New York, Los Angeles, Pittsburgh, Detroit, San Francisco and Minnesota Orchestras in the United States, as well as the London Symphony, Vienna Philharmonic, Berlin Philharmonic, Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra, Israel Philharmonic, and L'Orchestre de la Suisse Romande. His orchestral repertoire numbered over 450 works from all periods, and was matched by a repertoire of some sixty operas ranging from [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], [[Giuseppe Fortunino Francesco Verdi|Verdi]], [[Giacomo Antonio Domenico Michele Secondo Maria Puccini|Puccini]] and [[Richard Wagner|Wagner]] to the more contemporary [[Sergei Sergeyevich Prokofiev|Prokofiev]], [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k|Bart\u00f3k]], [[Benjamin Britten|Britten]], [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly|Kod\u00e1ly]], [[Francis Jean Marcel Poulenc|Poulenc]] and [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]]. Kert\u00e9sz was part of a rich musical tradition that produced fellow [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[conducting|conductors]] [[Fritz Reiner]], [[Antal Dor\u00e1ti]], [[J\u00e1nos Ferencsik]], [[Eugene Ormandy]], [[George Szell]], [[J\u00e1nos F\u00fcrst]], [[Ferenc Fricsay]], and Sir [[Georg Solti]].\n\nThrough his gramophone recordings, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz has been rediscovered by a new and younger audience, and has increasingly come to be regarded as one of the greatest conductors of all time {{citation needed}}.\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Childhood===\nKert\u00e9sz was born in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]], in 1929, the first child of Margit Muresian and Mikl\u00f3s Kert\u00e9sz. His sister, Vera, was born four years later. Mikl\u00f3s Kert\u00e9sz, born in [[Sz\u00e9cs\u00e9ny]], Hungary into a large [[Jew]]ish family, was the director of a leather-works and died of appendicitis in 1938. An energetic, intellectually gifted woman, Margit Muresian Kert\u00e9sz went to work to support her family. Despite strictures against women working professionally in Hungarian society during the first half of the twentieth century, Margit was steadily promoted until she ran the office where she was employed. At an early age Kert\u00e9sz showed a great affinity for music, and began [[violin]] lessons. \"When I was six and started music,\" he told a ''High Fidelity'' interviewer, \"it was 1935 and cruel things were going on in Europe ... I found my 'exile' in music, practicing the piano, the fiddle, and writing little compositions.\"<ref>\"Interview with Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz,\" ''High Fidelity Magazine'' 19, No. 12 (December 1969).</ref>\n\n===World War II and the Holocaust===\nWith the failure of Hungary's efforts to negotiate an armistice with the western Allies, German forces occupied Hungary on 19 March 1944. Aware of what was happening to [[Jew]]s throughout Europe, the family went into hiding. Most of Kert\u00e9sz's extended family were deported to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] in July 1944 and did not survive the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].\n\nAt the insistence of his mother, and despite the wartime interruptions of air raids, deportations, starvation and invasions by both Germans and later, the Russians, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz continued his musical studies. By the time he was twelve, Kert\u00e9sz began to study the [[piano]] and composition in addition to the violin. The young Kert\u00e9sz, along with his sister, took advantage of Budapest's rich cultural life and attended symphonic or operatic performances almost every evening. It was at this time that Kert\u00e9sz decided to become a conductor. After the war, he resumed his formal studies and attended the K\u00f6lcsey-[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] where, in 1947, he graduated with honors.\n\nThat same year, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz enrolled as a scholarship student at the Royal Academy of Music, now the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music]] in [[Budapest]], where he studied [[violin]], [[piano]] and [[Musical composition|composition]] with [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly]], [[Leo Weiner]] and [[Rezs\u0151 K\u00f3kai]]. Developing his keen interest in [[conducting]], Kert\u00e9sz became a student of [[J\u00e1nos Ferencsik]] and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Somogyi. At the [[Music school|conservatory]], Kert\u00e9sz also met his wife, the lyric [[soprano]] Edith Gancs, whom he married in 1951. She later changed her name to [[Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry]]. The gifted musical pair were part of a talented cohort of musicians. Musically, Kert\u00e9sz was most influenced by L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Somogyi, [[Bruno Walter]] and [[Otto Klemperer]], then the director of the [[Budapest Opera]].\n\n==Career==\nOn 17 December 1948, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz made his debut as a conductor with an all-Mozart programme.\n\n===Budapest===\nFrom 1953 to 1955, Kert\u00e9sz was chosen as Chief Conductor or the Philharmonic Orchestra at [[Gy\u0151r]], a post that he held for two years. During this period he had the opportunity to develop a broad symphonic repertoire, leading the [[Budapest]] Opera Orchestra from 1955 to 1957, and working as an Assistant Professor of Conducting at the Franz Liszt Academy of Music. After the upheaval of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian Revolution]], and with a young family in tow, Kert\u00e9sz left [[Hungary]]. Offered a fellowship to the [[Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia]] in [[Rome]], Kert\u00e9sz studied with [[Fernando Previtali]] while his wife, Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry sang at the [[Theater Bremen|Bremen Opera]]. Kert\u00e9sz graduated with distinction, and was given the highest award of the Accademia, the \"Premio d'Atri.\"  Moreover, Previtali chose Kert\u00e9sz for his \"Corso di Perfezionamento\" for two successive seasons, during which Kert\u00e9sz conducted the Santa Cecilia Orchestra forty times.\n\nAfter completing his studies in Rome, Kert\u00e9sz was engaged as a guest conductor of the [[Hamburger Symphoniker|Hamburg Symphony Orchestra]] and the [[Hamburg]] State Opera. Guest conducting there, as well as in [[Wiesbaden]] and [[Hanover]], he electrified German audiences with his masterful direction of ''[[Fidelio]]'' and ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''.\n\n===Augsburg Opera===\nIn March 1960, Kert\u00e9sz was invited to become General Music Director of the [[Augsburg]] Opera\u2014a post especially created for him. There he conducted performances of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s ''[[The Magic Flute]]'', ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail|The Abduction from the Seraglio]]'', ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'', and ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', earning himself a reputation as one of the finest interpreters of Mozart's work. With exhilarating performances of [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Rigoletto]]'', ''[[Don Carlos]]'', ''[[Otello]]'' and ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'', and [[Richard Strauss]]'s ''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'', ''[[Arabella]]'', and ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', Kert\u00e9sz also proved himself a master of the finest of Italian Romantic operas. Invited to the [[Salzburg Festival]], he conducted ''The Abduction from the Seraglio'' in 1961, and ''The Magic Flute'' in 1963. During this time, Kert\u00e9sz also gave the first of many performances at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], with the [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[San Francisco Opera]], [[North German Radio Symphony Orchestra]], [[Hamburg Symphony]], [[Munich Philharmonic]], [[Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Festival dei Due Mondi]] in [[Spoleto]] where he conducted Prokofiev's ''[[The Fiery Angel (opera)|The Fiery Angel]]'', and with [[Arthur Rubinstein]] in [[Paris]].\n\nKert\u00e9sz also made his earliest recordings, including Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 2 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 2]] and [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]]. Having already recorded for EMI/Columbia records, Kert\u00e9sz now signed an exclusive contract with Decca/London for whom he began to make dozens of prize-winning recordings. Already at this early stage in his career, Kert\u00e9sz's interpretations of Brahms and Dvo\u0159\u00e1k were highly regarded for their transparent textures and unmannered phrasing. In stark contrast to [[Herbert von Karajan]] and [[George Szell]], Kert\u00e9sz's music-making featured an unforced manner even when employing the fastest of tempi. Other elements that made a Kert\u00e9sz performance notable was the elasticity of tempi while adhering to the structural coherence of a given musical work. His British debut was with the [[Royal Liverpool Philharmonic|Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra]] in 1960. Kert\u00e9sz made his U.S. debut during the 1961-62 season, also beginning an association with the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra whom he guest-conducted at [[Tel Aviv]]'s Mann Auditorium in March 1962. Eventually, Kert\u00e9sz conducted over 378 compositions with the Israel Philharmonic over an eleven-year period.\n\nWithin just four years, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz had established a lasting international reputation as a conductor.\n\n===Cologne Opera===\nIn 1964, Kert\u00e9sz received an appointment as the General Music Director of the [[Cologne Opera]] where he conducted the first German performance of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'' and Verdi's ''[[Stiffelio]]'', as well as the [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] operas ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'', ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' and ''The Magic Flute''.\n\nWhile he established a good rapport with the often critical Cologne audience, they were sometimes unhappy with his often fast tempi. His 1970 ''[[Aida]]'', with [[Martina Arroyo]] in the title role, with one interval and some cuts, lasted under three hours.\n\n===London Symphony Orchestra===\nRetaining his previous position as Director of the [[Cologne Opera]], he also became Principal Conductor of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] from 1965 to 1968, and made guest appearances at the [[Royal Opera House]], [[Covent Garden]]. During his three years as Principal Conductor of the LSO, Kert\u00e9sz gave superbly stylish, imaginative and deft performances. He was acclaimed for recordings with the ensemble of the nine [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] [[Symphony|symphonies]], which included the first complete recording of the [[Symphony No. 1 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 1]].<ref>Ray Minshull, ''Dvo\u0159\u00e1k Symphony No. 1'' (liner notes from the Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz recording).</ref>\n\nDuring this period in Kert\u00e9sz's career, in 1966, he also recorded ''[[Bluebeard's Castle]]'' with [[Christa Ludwig]] singing the role of Judith and [[Walter Berry (bass-baritone)|Walter Berry]] in the title role. Kert\u00e9sz's interpretation of Bart\u00f3k's difficult, brooding work is considered by many to be the benchmark performance of the opera; \"the playing of the London Symphony Orchestra, and Kert\u00e9sz's instinctive shaping of the drama . . . has never been surpassed.\"<ref>Andrew Clements, \"Bart\u00f3k: Bluebeard's Castle,\" ''The Guardian'' (Friday, 2 March 2001).</ref>\n\nKert\u00e9sz was a frequent guest conductor of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], the [[Vienna Philharmonic]], the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], and numerous other orchestras. He was appointed Principal Conductor of the [[Bamberg Symphony]] in 1973. The [[Cleveland Orchestra]] unsuccessfully bid for his appointment as musical director the year before. The orchestra players voted 96 to 2 to request the board to favour Kert\u00e9sz as the replacement of [[George Szell]]. In Chicago, he conducted his first performance at the Ravinia Festival in July 1967; he was the Festival's principal conductor from 1970 to 1972.\n\n==Death==\nOn 16 April 1973, while on a concert tour, Kert\u00e9sz [[drowning|drowned]] while swimming off the coast of [[Israel]] at [[Herzliya]].<ref>\"Obituary for Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz,\" ''The Musical Times'' 114, No. 1564 (1973), p. 632.</ref> He had been recording what would become a legendary version of [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]]' ''[[Variations on a Theme by Haydn]]'', as well as the complete Brahms symphonies. After his untimely death, and in tribute to him, the Vienna Philharmonic finished recording the ''Haydn Variations''.\n\nKert\u00e9sz was survived by his wife, operatic soprano Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry, his children, G\u00e1bor, P\u00e9ter, and Kathrin, his mother, Margit Muresian Kert\u00e9sz Halmos, and his sister, the graphic artist Vera Kert\u00e9sz.\n\n==International orchestras==\nIstv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz served as principal and or guest conductor under the following orchestras:\n[[Bamberg Symphony Orchestra]], [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], [[Cleveland Orchestra]], [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] (Amsterdam), Detroit Symphony Orchestra, G\u00fcrzenich Orchestra ([[Cologne, Germany|Cologne]]), [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], Japan Philharmonic Orchestra ([[Tokyo]]), [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], [[Minnesota Orchestra]], [[Philharmonia|New Philharmonia Orchestra]] (London), [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[New York Philharmonic]], [[Symphonieorchester des Bayerischen Rundfunks]] (Munich), Orquestre Nacional ([[Madrid]]), Orchestre Radio-T\u00e9l\u00e9vision ([[Paris]]), [[Orchestre de la Suisse Romande]] ([[Geneva]]), [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], [[Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra]], Radio Symphony Orchestra (Berlin), Opera Orchestra of Santa Cecila (Rome), [[San Francisco Symphony]], Symphonie Orchester des Norddeutschen Rundfunks ([[Hamburg]]), [[Royal Stockholm Philharmonic Orchestra]], Tonhalle-Orchester (Z\u00fcrich), [[Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\n==Discography==\nHis many recordings include the first complete recording of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]''.<ref>see:<br />[[Library of Congress]], Online Catalog <br /> [https://portal.d-nb.de/opac.htm?query=Kertesz%2C+Istvan&method=simpleSearch Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Deutsches Musikarchiv] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723000059/https://portal.d-nb.de/opac.htm?query=Kertesz,+Istvan&method=simpleSearch |date=2011-07-23 }} <br />[http://aleph18.onb.ac.at/F/L62TU2HMAI2RLGT3K9F4DIKUICV74G7GSSKEUG8YUX7HSVSEAE-60895?func=find-b&find_code=WRD&adjacent=N&request=Kertesz%2C+Istvan \u00d6sterreichische Nationalbibliothek Katalog der Musiksammlung] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531194917/http://aleph18.onb.ac.at/F/L62TU2HMAI2RLGT3K9F4DIKUICV74G7GSSKEUG8YUX7HSVSEAE-60895?func=find-b&find_code=WRD&adjacent=N&request=Kertesz,+Istvan |date=2011-05-31 }}</ref> He was also the first to record the complete [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] symphonies and his interpretations of them are still considered classics of their kind. Pianists [[Clifford Curzon]], [[Hans Richter-Haaser]], [[Vladimir Ashkenazy]] and [[Julius Katchen]] each made fine records with Kert\u00e9sz, among which the Mozart concertos are particularly inspired. With his renditions of [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly|Kod\u00e1ly]]'s big orchestral works, and given his precise yet passionate conducting style, Kert\u00e9sz was particularly well-suited to get the full orchestral swoop and swoon endemic to ''Psalmus Hungaricus'' and the ''Peacock Variations''. The sonority Kert\u00e9sz managed to elicit from the [[London Symphony Orchestra|LSO]] was expertly executed. Little wonder that [[Barry Tuckwell]], the principal [[French horn|hornist]] of the LSO, spoke of the \u00e9lan and enthusiasm Kert\u00e9sz could coax out of the orchestra, many of whose members Tuckwell regarded as \"old codgers not bloody likely to dance to any youngster's tune.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n*[[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k|Bart\u00f3k]], ''[[Bluebeard's Castle]]'' ([[Christa Ludwig|Ludwig]], [[Walter Berry (opera singer)|Berry]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 311\n*Bart\u00f3k, [[Piano Concerto No. 3 (Bart\u00f3k)|Piano Concerto No. 3]] in E, Sz. 119 ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6209\n*[[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]], [[Piano Concerto No. 3 (Beethoven)|Piano Concerto No. 3]] in C minor, Op. 37, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, OPERA EPK 3269\n*Beethoven, ''[[Coriolan Overture]]'', Op. 62, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, ARIOLA/Bacc. ZK 79287\n*Beethoven\n**[[Fidelio|''Leonore'' Overture No. 3]], Op. 72b\n**[[Symphony No. 2 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 2]] in D major, Op. 36, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, OPERA EPK S 91\n**[[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]] in B Flat Major, Op. 60, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, DENON COGQ-1008\n*[[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]], [[Serenades (Brahms)|Serenade No. 1]] in D major, Op. 11, London Symphony Orchestra (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6340\n*Brahms, [[Serenades (Brahms)|Serenade No. 2]] in A major, Op. 16, London Symphony Orchestra (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6368\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 1 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 1]] in C minor, Op. 68, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6675\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 2]] in D major, Op. 73, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6172\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 3 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 3]] in F major, Op. 90, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6677\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] in E minor, Op. 98, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1972), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6678\n*Brahms, [[Variations on a Theme by Haydn]], Op. 56, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6677\n*[[Anton Bruckner|Bruckner]], [[Symphony No. 4 (Bruckner)|Symphony No. 4]] in E-flat major, \"Romantic\", London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6227\n*[[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]], ''[[Don Pasquale]]'' (Sciutti, Corena, Krause, Oncina), [[Vienna State Opera|Vienna State Opera Orchestra and Choir]] (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 280/81\n*[[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], Serenade in D minor for Winds, Op. 44, London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6368\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, Overtures: ''In Nature's Realm'', ''Carneval'', ''Otello'', ''Scherzo Capriccioso'' London Symphony Orchestra (1966, 1965, 1965, 1963 respectively), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6348\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''[[Requiem (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Requiem]]'', Op. 89 (Lorengar, Komlossy, Ilosfalvy, Krause), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 416/7\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''Slavonic Dances Nos. 1, 3, 8, 9, 10'', [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6024\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, Symphonic Poems: ''Hussite'', ''My Home'', ''The Noonday Witch'', ''The Water Goblin'', London Symphony Orchestra, (1965, 1965, 1970, 1970 respectively) [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6543\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''[[Symphonic Variations (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphonic Variations]]'', London Symphony Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6510\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 1 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 1 in C minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6288\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 2 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 2 in B flat major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6289\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 3 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 3 in E flat major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6290\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 4 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 4 in D minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6257\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 5 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 5 in F major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6273\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 6 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 6 in D major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6253\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 7 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 7 in D minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6115\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 8 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 8 in G major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6044\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 9 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 9 in E minor \"From the New World\"]] London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6291\n*[[Werner Egk]], ''[[Furchtlosigkeit und Wohlwollen]]'', ([[Fritz Wunderlich|Wunderlich]]) [[Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra]] & Chorus, [[Orfeo (record label)|Orfeo]] 510011 \t\n*[[George Gershwin|Gershwin]], ''[[Rhapsody in Blue]]'' ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6411\n*[[Edvard Grieg|Grieg]], [[Piano Concerto (Grieg)|Piano Concerto]] in A minor ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SMD 1152\n*[[Joseph Haydn|Haydn]]\n**[[Symphony No. 45 (Haydn)|Symphony No. 45]] in F-sharp minor, \"Farewell\" Bamberg Symphony Orchestra,\n**[[Symphony No. 104 (Haydn)|Symphony No. 104]] in D major, \"London\" ARIOLA/Bacc. ZK 80051\n*[[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly|Kod\u00e1ly]], ''[[H\u00e1ry J\u00e1nos]]'', [[Edinburgh Festival]] Chorus and the London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 399/400\n*Kod\u00e1ly\n**[[H\u00e1ry J\u00e1nos|H\u00e1ry J\u00e1nos Suite]]''\n**''Dances of [[Galanta]]'' (Sz\u00f6nyi), London Symphony Orchestra (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6136\n*Kod\u00e1ly, ''Psalmus Hungaricus'', Op. 13, London Symphony Orchestra (1969/70), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6497\n*Kod\u00e1ly, ''Peacock Variations'', London Symphony Orchestra (1969/70), [[Decca Records|DECCA]]\n*[[Franz Liszt|Liszt]]\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 1 (Liszt)|Piano Concerto No. 1]] in E-flat major, S. 124\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 2 (Liszt)|Piano Concerto No. 2]] in A major (Karolyi), S. 125, Julian von Karolyi, [[Philharmonia Hungarica]] (1961), [[EMI]] C 047 - 50517\n*[[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'', K. 588 (selections) ([[Lucia Popp|Popp]], [[Brigitte Fassbaender|Fassbaender]], Krause), Vienna Haydn Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]]  433 066-2\n*Mozart, ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail]]'', ([[Fritz Wunderlich|Wunderlich]], Putz, Holm, Wolf, Wohlfahrt, Littasy), K.384, [[Salzburger Festspiele]] (1961), [[Decca Records|DECCA]]  DK 11 560/1-2\n*Mozart, ''[[The Magic Flute|Die Zauberfl\u00f6te]]'', K. 620 ([[Lucia Popp|Popp]], Krauss, [[Werner Krenn|Krenn]]), Vienna Haydn Orchestra (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] DK 11 560/1-2\n*Mozart, ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'', K. 621 ([[Teresa Berganza|Berganza]], Casula, [[Brigitte Fassbaender|Fassbaender]], [[Lucia Popp|Popp]], Krenn, Franc), [[Vienna State Opera|Vienna State Opera Orchestra and Choir]] (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 357/59\n*Mozart, \"Masonic Funeral Music\", (Fischer, Krenn, Krause), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6409\n*Mozart:\n**Piano Concerto No. 8 in C major, K. 246\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 9 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 9]] in E-flat major, \"Jeunehomme\", K. 271\n**Rondo in A minor, K. 511 ([[Vladimir Ashkenazy|Ashkenazy]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6259\n*Mozart\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 17 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 17]] in G major, K. 453\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 26 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 26]] in D major, \"Coronation\", K. 537 (Richter-Haaser), [[Philharmonia|London Philharmonia Orchestra]], [[EMI]] 1 047 - 50506\n*Mozart\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 23 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 23]] in A major, K. 488\n**[[Piano Concerto No. 24 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 24]] in C minor, K. 491 ([[Clifford Curzon|Curzon]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1967, [[Decca Records|DECCA]]  SXL 6354\n*Mozart, [[Piano Concerto No. 27 (Mozart)|Piano Concerto No. 27]] in B flat major, K.595 ([[Clifford Curzon|Curzon]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1967), [[Philips Records|Philips-DECCA]] 456757\n*Mozart, ''\"Mozart Festival\"'', Vol. I, Vienna Haydn Orchestra, [[Decca Records|DECCA]] DK 11 536/1-2\n*Mozart, ''\"Mozart Festival\"'', Vol. II, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, [[Decca Records|DECCA]] DK 11 560/1-2\n*Mozart, [[Requiem (Mozart)|Requiem]] in D minor, K. 626 ([[Elly Ameling|Ameling]], [[Marilyn Horne|Horne]], Benelli, Franc), Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SMD 1242\n*Mozart\n**[[Sinfonia Concertante for Violin, Viola and Orchestra|Sinfonia Concertante]] in E-flat major, K. 364\n**[[Clarinet Concerto (Mozart)|Clarinet Concerto]] in A major, K. 622 (Lautenbacher, Koch, D\u00f6rr), Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, Turnabout STV 34 098\n*Mozart\n**Sonata for Organ and Orchestra No. 5\n**Sonata for Organ and Orchestra No. 11 in D, K. 245\n**Sonata for Organ and Orchestra No. 13\n**Sonata for Organ and Orchestra No. 14 (Ella), Corelli Chamber Orchestra, Hungaraton HCD 128662\n*Mozart\n**[[Symphony No. 25 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 25]] in G minor, K. 183/173&nbsp;dB\n**[[Symphony No. 29 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 29]] in A major, K. 201\n**[[Symphony No. 35 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 35]] in D major, \"Haffner\", K.385, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1972, 1972, 1962 respectively), [[Decca Records|DECCA]]/Vienna (Sofiensaal) KING 230E 51016\n*Mozart\n**Symphony No. 33 in B-flat major, K. 319\n**[[Symphony No. 39 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 39]] in E-flat major, K. 543, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6056\n*Mozart\n**[[Symphony No. 36 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 36]] in C major, \"Linz\", K. 425\n**[[Symphony No. 40 (Mozart)|Symphony No. 40]] in G Minor, K. 550, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963,1972 respectively), Vienna (Sofiensaal)/KING\n*Mozart\n**''[[Eine kleine Nachtmusik]]'' in G major, K. 525 Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6091\n*Mozart, [[Coronation Mass (Mozart)|Coronation Mass]] in C major, K. 317 Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, OPERA EPK 3257\n*[[Sergei Prokofiev|Prokofiev]], [[Piano Concerto No. 3 (Prokofiev)|Piano Concerto No. 3]] in C major, op. 26 ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6411\n*[[Maurice Ravel|Ravel]], [[Piano Concerto (Ravel)|Concerto for Piano and Orchestra]] in G ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6209\n*Ravel, [[Piano Concerto for the Left Hand (Ravel)|Concerto for the Left Hand]] in D major ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6411\n*[[Ottorino Respighi|Respighi]]\n**''[[Pini di Roma|Pines of Rome]]''\n**''[[Fontane di Roma|Fountains of Rome]]''\n**''The Birds (Gli uccelli)'', London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6401\n*[[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini]], ''Stabat Mater'' [[Pilar Lorengar]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], [[Yvonne Minton]], Sotin, London Symphony Orchestra (1970/1), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6524\n*[[Dmitri Shostakovich|Shostakovich]], [[Symphony No. 5 (Shostakovich)|Symphony No. 5]] in D minor, Op. 47, [[Orchestre de la Suisse Romande]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6018\n*[[Franz Schubert|Schubert]]\n**[[Symphony No. 1 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 1]] in D major, D. 82, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6552\n**[[Symphony No. 2 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 2]] in B-flat major, D. 125, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6552\n**[[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 3]] in D major, D. 200, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6553\n**[[Symphony No. 4 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 4]] in C minor, \"Tragic\", D. 417, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6483\n**[[Symphony No. 5 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 5]] in B-flat major, D. 485, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6483\n**[[Symphony No. 6 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 6]] in C major, \"The Little C major\", D. 589, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6553\n**[[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 8/7]] in B minor, [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|\"Unfinished\"]], D. 759, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL6090\n**[[Symphony No. 9 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 9/7/8]] in C major, \"The Great C major\", D. 944, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6089\n**Overtures ''Des Teufels Lustschloss'', D. 84, in the Italian style in C major, D. 591, ''Fierabras'', D. 796, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL6090\n*[[Robert Schumann|Schumann]], [[Piano Concerto (Schumann)|Piano Concerto]] in A minor, Op. 54 ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SMD 1152\n*[[Bed\u0159ich Smetana|Smetana]], ''Bohemian Rhapsody'': ''[[Vltava|The Moldau]]'', ''[[The Bartered Bride]] Overture'', [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6024\n*[[Franz Strauss]], Horn Concerto, Op. 8, ([[Barry Tuckwell]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6285\n*[[Richard Strauss]], Horn Concertos, Nos. 1-2, (Barry Tuckwell), London Symphony Orchestra (1966), Decca BDX1259 \n*[[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]], ''[[Otello]]'', [[Augsburg]] State Opera (1962), OPERA EPK 1220.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Sadie, Stanley. ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', Macmillan, 1980.\n* Jaeger, Stefan. ''Das Atlantisbuch der Dirigenten'', Atlantis Musikbuch-Verlag, 1985.\n* Lyman, Darryl. ''Great Jews in Music'', J. D. Publishers, 1986.\n* Holmes, John L.: ''Conductors. A record collector's guide'', Gollancz Ltd. 1988.\n* Myers, Kurtz. ''Index to record reviews 1984\u20131987'', G.K. Hall, 1989.\n* P\u00e2ris, Alain. ''Dictionnaire des interpretes et de l'interpretation musicale au XX siecle'', Robert Laffont, 1989.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=q33147|label=Istvan Kert\u00e9sz}}\n*[http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/wunderlich/bios/kertesz.htm Fritz Wunderlich Colleagues]\n\n{{LSO principal conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kertesz, Istvan}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Deaths by drowning]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Israel]]\n[[Category:Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia alumni]]\n[[Category:Franz Liszt Academy of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:London Symphony Orchestra principal conductors]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British musicians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz''' (28 August 1929{{spaced ndash}}16 April 1973) was an internationally acclaimed [[Jewish]] [[Hungary|Hungarian]] orchestral and operatic [[conducting|conductor]] who, throughout his brief but distinguished career led many of the world's great orchestras, including the Cleveland, Chicago, Philadelphia, New York, Los Angeles, Pittsburgh, Detroit, San Francisco and Minnesota Orchestras in the United States, as well as the London Symphony, Vienna Philharmonic, Berlin Philharmonic, Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra, Israel Philharmonic, and L'Orchestre de la Suisse Romande. His orchestral repertoire numbered over 450 works from all periods, and was matched by a repertoire of some sixty operas ranging from [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], [[Giuseppe Fortunino Francesco Verdi|Verdi]], [[Giacomo Antonio Domenico Michele Secondo Maria Puccini|Puccini]] and [[Richard Wagner|Wagner]] to the more contemporary [[Sergei Sergeyevich Prokofiev|Prokofiev]], [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k|Bart\u00f3k]], [[Benjamin Britten|Britten]], [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly|Kod\u00e1ly]], [[Francis Jean Marcel Poulenc|Poulenc]] and [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]]. Kert\u00e9sz was part of a rich musical tradition that produced fellow [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[conducting|conductors]] [[Fritz Reiner]], [[Antal Dor\u00e1ti]], [[J\u00e1nos Ferencsik]], [[Eugene Ormandy]], [[George Szell]], [[J\u00e1nos F\u00fcrst]], [[Ferenc Fricsay]], and Sir [[Georg Solti]].\n\nThrough his gramophone recordings, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz has been rediscovered by a new and younger audience, and has increasingly come to be regarded as one of the greatest conductors of all time.{{citation needed}}\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Childhood===\nKert\u00e9sz was born in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]], in 1929, the first child of Margit Muresian and Mikl\u00f3s Kert\u00e9sz. His sister, Vera, was born four years later. Mikl\u00f3s Kert\u00e9sz, born in [[Sz\u00e9cs\u00e9ny]], Hungary into a large [[Jew]]ish family, was the director of a leather-works and died of appendicitis in 1938. An energetic, intellectually gifted woman, Margit Muresian Kert\u00e9sz went to work to support her family. Despite strictures against women working professionally in Hungarian society during the first half of the twentieth century, Margit was steadily promoted until she ran the office where she was employed. At an early age Kert\u00e9sz showed a great affinity for music, and began [[violin]] lessons. \"When I was six and started music,\" he told a ''High Fidelity'' interviewer, \"it was 1935 and cruel things were going on in Europe ... I found my 'exile' in music, practicing the piano, the fiddle, and writing little compositions.\"<ref>\"Interview with Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz,\" ''High Fidelity Magazine'' 19, No. 12 (December 1969).</ref>\n\n===World War II and the Holocaust===\nWith the failure of Hungary's efforts to negotiate an armistice with the western Allies, German forces occupied Hungary on 19 March 1944. Aware of what was happening to [[Jew]]s throughout Europe, the family went into hiding. Most of Kert\u00e9sz's extended family were deported to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] in July 1944 and did not survive the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].\n\nAt the insistence of his mother, and despite the wartime interruptions of air raids, deportations, starvation and invasions by both Germans and later, the Russians, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz continued his musical studies. By the time he was twelve, Kert\u00e9sz began to study the [[piano]] and composition in addition to the violin. The young Kert\u00e9sz, along with his sister, took advantage of Budapest's rich cultural life and attended symphonic or operatic performances almost every evening. It was at this time that Kert\u00e9sz decided to become a conductor. After the war, he resumed his formal studies and attended the K\u00f6lcsey-[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] where, in 1947, he graduated with honors.\n\nThat same year, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz enrolled as a scholarship student at the Royal Academy of Music, now the [[Franz Liszt Academy of Music]] in [[Budapest]], where he studied [[violin]], [[piano]] and [[Musical composition|composition]] with [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly]], [[Leo Weiner]] and [[Rezs\u0151 K\u00f3kai]]. Developing his keen interest in [[conducting]], Kert\u00e9sz became a student of [[J\u00e1nos Ferencsik]] and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Somogyi. At the [[Music school|conservatory]], Kert\u00e9sz also met his wife, the lyric [[soprano]] Edith Gancs, whom he married in 1951. She later changed her name to [[Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry]]. The gifted musical pair were part of a talented cohort of musicians. Musically, Kert\u00e9sz was most influenced by L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Somogyi, [[Bruno Walter]] and [[Otto Klemperer]], then the director of the [[Budapest Opera]].\n\n==Career==\nOn 17 December 1948, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz made his debut as a conductor with an all-Mozart programme.\n\n===Budapest===\nFrom 1953 to 1955, Kert\u00e9sz was chosen as Chief Conductor or the Philharmonic Orchestra at [[Gy\u0151r]], a post that he held for two years. During this period he had the opportunity to develop a broad symphonic repertoire, leading the [[Budapest]] Opera Orchestra from 1955 to 1957, and working as an Assistant Professor of Conducting at the Franz Liszt Academy of Music. After the upheaval of the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian Revolution]], and with a young family in tow, Kert\u00e9sz left [[Hungary]]. Offered a fellowship to the [[Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia]] in [[Rome]], Kert\u00e9sz studied with [[Fernando Previtali]] while his wife, Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry sang at the [[Theater Bremen|Bremen Opera]]. Kert\u00e9sz graduated with distinction, and was given the highest award of the Accademia, the \"Premio d'Atri.\"  Moreover, Previtali chose Kert\u00e9sz for his \"Corso di Perfezionamento\" for two successive seasons, during which Kert\u00e9sz conducted the Santa Cecilia Orchestra forty times.\n\nAfter completing his studies in Rome, Kert\u00e9sz was engaged as a guest conductor of the [[Hamburger Symphoniker|Hamburg Symphony Orchestra]] and the [[Hamburg]] State Opera. Guest conducting there, as well as in [[Wiesbaden]] and [[Hanover]], he electrified German audiences with his masterful direction of ''[[Fidelio]]'' and ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]''.\n\n===Augsburg Opera===\nIn March 1960, Kert\u00e9sz was invited to become General Music Director of the [[Augsburg]] Opera\u2014a post especially created for him. There he conducted performances of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s ''[[The Magic Flute]]'', ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail|The Abduction from the Seraglio]]'', ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'', and ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', earning himself a reputation as one of the finest interpreters of Mozart's work. With exhilarating performances of [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Rigoletto]]'', ''[[Don Carlos]]'', ''[[Otello]]'' and ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'', and [[Richard Strauss]]'s ''[[Salome (opera)|Salome]]'', ''[[Arabella]]'', and ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', Kert\u00e9sz also proved himself a master of the finest of Italian Romantic operas. Invited to the [[Salzburg Festival]], he conducted ''The Abduction from the Seraglio'' in 1961, and ''The Magic Flute'' in 1963. During this time, Kert\u00e9sz also gave the first of many performances at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], with the [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[San Francisco Opera]], [[North German Radio Symphony Orchestra]], [[Hamburg Symphony]], [[Munich Philharmonic]], [[Bavarian Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Festival dei Due Mondi]] in [[Spoleto]] where he conducted Prokofiev's ''[[The Fiery Angel (opera)|The Fiery Angel]]'', and with [[Arthur Rubinstein]] in [[Paris]].\n\nKert\u00e9sz also made his earliest recordings, including Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 2 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 2]] and [[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]]. Having already recorded for EMI/Columbia records, Kert\u00e9sz now signed an exclusive contract with Decca/London for whom he began to make dozens of prize-winning recordings. Already at this early stage in his career, Kert\u00e9sz's interpretations of Brahms and Dvo\u0159\u00e1k were highly regarded for their transparent textures and unmannered phrasing. In stark contrast to [[Herbert von Karajan]] and [[George Szell]], Kert\u00e9sz's music-making featured an unforced manner even when employing the fastest of tempi. Other elements that made a Kert\u00e9sz performance notable was the elasticity of tempi while adhering to the structural coherence of a given musical work. His British debut was with the [[Royal Liverpool Philharmonic|Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra]] in 1960. Kert\u00e9sz made his U.S. debut during the 1961-62 season, also beginning an association with the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra whom he guest-conducted at [[Tel Aviv]]'s Mann Auditorium in March 1962. Eventually, Kert\u00e9sz conducted over 378 compositions with the Israel Philharmonic over an eleven-year period.\n\nWithin just four years, Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz had established a lasting international reputation as a conductor.\n\n===Cologne Opera===\nIn 1964, Kert\u00e9sz received an appointment as the General Music Director of the [[Cologne Opera]] where he conducted the first German performance of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'' and Verdi's ''[[Stiffelio]]'', as well as the [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] operas ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'', ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', ''Cos\u00ec fan tutte'' and ''The Magic Flute''.\n\nWhile he established a good rapport with the often critical Cologne audience, they were sometimes unhappy with his often fast tempi. His 1970 ''[[Aida]]'', with [[Martina Arroyo]] in the title role, with one interval and some cuts, lasted under three hours.\n\n===London Symphony Orchestra===\nRetaining his previous position as Director of the [[Cologne Opera]], he also became Principal Conductor of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] from 1965 to 1968, and made guest appearances at the [[Royal Opera House]], [[Covent Garden]]. During his three years as Principal Conductor of the LSO, Kert\u00e9sz gave superbly stylish, imaginative and deft performances. He was acclaimed for recordings with the ensemble of the nine [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] [[Symphony|symphonies]], which included the first complete recording of the [[Symphony No. 1 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 1]].<ref>Ray Minshull, ''Dvo\u0159\u00e1k Symphony No. 1'' (liner notes from the Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz recording).</ref>\n\nDuring this period in Kert\u00e9sz's career, in 1966, he also recorded ''[[Bluebeard's Castle]]'' with [[Christa Ludwig]] singing the role of Judith and [[Walter Berry (bass-baritone)|Walter Berry]] in the title role. Kert\u00e9sz's interpretation of Bart\u00f3k's difficult, brooding work is considered by many to be the benchmark performance of the opera; \"the playing of the London Symphony Orchestra, and Kert\u00e9sz's instinctive shaping of the drama . . . has never been surpassed.\"<ref>Andrew Clements, \"Bart\u00f3k: Bluebeard's Castle,\" ''The Guardian'' (Friday, 2 March 2001).</ref>\n\nKert\u00e9sz was a frequent guest conductor of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], the [[Vienna Philharmonic]], the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], and numerous other orchestras. He was appointed Principal Conductor of the [[Bamberg Symphony]] in 1973. The [[Cleveland Orchestra]] unsuccessfully bid for his appointment as musical director the year before. The orchestra players voted 96 to 2 to request the board to favour Kert\u00e9sz as the replacement of [[George Szell]]. In Chicago, he conducted his first performance at the Ravinia Festival in July 1967; he was the Festival's principal conductor from 1970 to 1972.\n\n==Death==\nOn 16 April 1973, while on a concert tour, Kert\u00e9sz [[drowning|drowned]] while swimming off the coast of [[Israel]] at [[Herzliya]].<ref>\"Obituary for Istv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz,\" ''The Musical Times'' 114, No. 1564 (1973), p. 632.</ref> He had been recording what would become a legendary version of [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]]' ''[[Variations on a Theme by Haydn]]'', as well as the complete Brahms symphonies. After his untimely death, and in tribute to him, the Vienna Philharmonic finished recording the ''Haydn Variations''.\n\nKert\u00e9sz was survived by his wife, operatic soprano Edith Kert\u00e9sz-Gabry, his children, G\u00e1bor, P\u00e9ter, and Kathrin, his mother, Margit Muresian Kert\u00e9sz Halmos, and his sister, the graphic artist Vera Kert\u00e9sz.\n\n==International orchestras==\nIstv\u00e1n Kert\u00e9sz served as principal and or guest conductor under the following orchestras:\n[[Bamberg Symphony Orchestra]], [[Berlin Philharmonic]], [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]], [[Cleveland Orchestra]], [[Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra]] (Amsterdam), Detroit Symphony Orchestra, G\u00fcrzenich Orchestra ([[Cologne, Germany|Cologne]]), [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], Japan Philharmonic Orchestra ([[Tokyo]]), [[London Symphony Orchestra]], [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], [[Minnesota Orchestra]], [[Philharmonia|New Philharmonia Orchestra]] (London), [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[New York Philharmonic]], [[Symphonieorchester des Bayerischen Rundfunks]] (Munich), Orquestre Nacional ([[Madrid]]), Orchestre Radio-T\u00e9l\u00e9vision ([[Paris]]), [[Orchestre de la Suisse Romande]] ([[Geneva]]), [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], [[Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra]], Radio Symphony Orchestra (Berlin), Opera Orchestra of Santa Cecila (Rome), [[San Francisco Symphony]], Symphonie Orchester des Norddeutschen Rundfunks ([[Hamburg]]), [[Royal Stockholm Philharmonic Orchestra]], Tonhalle-Orchester (Z\u00fcrich), [[Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\n==Discography==\nHis many recordings include the first complete recording of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]''.<ref>see:<br />[[Library of Congress]], Online Catalog <br /> [https://portal.d-nb.de/opac.htm?query=Kertesz%2C+Istvan&method=simpleSearch Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Deutsches Musikarchiv] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723000059/https://portal.d-nb.de/opac.htm?query=Kertesz,+Istvan&method=simpleSearch |date=2011-07-23 }} <br />[http://aleph18.onb.ac.at/F/L62TU2HMAI2RLGT3K9F4DIKUICV74G7GSSKEUG8YUX7HSVSEAE-60895?func=find-b&find_code=WRD&adjacent=N&request=Kertesz%2C+Istvan \u00d6sterreichische Nationalbibliothek Katalog der Musiksammlung] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531194917/http://aleph18.onb.ac.at/F/L62TU2HMAI2RLGT3K9F4DIKUICV74G7GSSKEUG8YUX7HSVSEAE-60895?func=find-b&find_code=WRD&adjacent=N&request=Kertesz,+Istvan |date=2011-05-31 }}</ref> He was also the first to record the complete [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]] symphonies and his interpretations of them are still considered classics of their kind. Pianists [[Clifford Curzon]], [[Hans Richter-Haaser]], [[Vladimir Ashkenazy]] and [[Julius Katchen]] each made fine records with Kert\u00e9sz, among which the Mozart concertos are particularly inspired. With his renditions of [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly|Kod\u00e1ly]]'s big orchestral works, and given his precise yet passionate conducting style, Kert\u00e9sz was particularly well-suited to get the full orchestral swoop and swoon endemic to ''Psalmus Hungaricus'' and the ''Peacock Variations''. The sonority Kert\u00e9sz managed to elicit from the [[London Symphony Orchestra|LSO]] was expertly executed. Little wonder that [[Barry Tuckwell]], the principal [[French horn|hornist]] of the LSO, spoke of the \u00e9lan and enthusiasm Kert\u00e9sz could coax out of the orchestra, many of whose members Tuckwell regarded as \"old codgers not bloody likely to dance to any youngster's tune.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n*[[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k|Bart\u00f3k]], ''[[Bluebeard's Castle]]'' ([[Christa Ludwig|Ludwig]], [[Walter Berry (opera singer)|Berry]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 311\n*Bart\u00f3k, [[Piano Concerto No. 3 (Bart\u00f3k)|Piano Concerto No. 3]] in E, Sz. 119 ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6209\n*[[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]], [[Piano Concerto No. 3 (Beethoven)|Piano Concerto No. 3]] in C minor, Op. 37, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, OPERA EPK 3269\n*Beethoven, ''[[Coriolan Overture]]'', Op. 62, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, ARIOLA/Bacc. ZK 79287\n*Beethoven\n**[[Fidelio|''Leonore'' Overture No. 3]], Op. 72b\n**[[Symphony No. 2 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 2]] in D major, Op. 36, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, OPERA EPK S 91\n**[[Symphony No. 4 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 4]] in B Flat Major, Op. 60, Bamberg Symphony Orchestra, DENON COGQ-1008\n*[[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]], [[Serenades (Brahms)|Serenade No. 1]] in D major, Op. 11, London Symphony Orchestra (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6340\n*Brahms, [[Serenades (Brahms)|Serenade No. 2]] in A major, Op. 16, London Symphony Orchestra (1967), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6368\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 1 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 1]] in C minor, Op. 68, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6675\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 2 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 2]] in D major, Op. 73, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6172\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 3 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 3]] in F major, Op. 90, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6677\n*Brahms, [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] in E minor, Op. 98, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1972), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6678\n*Brahms, [[Variations on a Theme by Haydn]], Op. 56, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1973), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6677\n*[[Anton Bruckner|Bruckner]], [[Symphony No. 4 (Bruckner)|Symphony No. 4]] in E-flat major, \"Romantic\", London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6227\n*[[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]], ''[[Don Pasquale]]'' (Sciutti, Corena, Krause, Oncina), [[Vienna State Opera|Vienna State Opera Orchestra and Choir]] (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 280/81\n*[[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], Serenade in D minor for Winds, Op. 44, London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6368\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, Overtures: ''In Nature's Realm'', ''Carneval'', ''Otello'', ''Scherzo Capriccioso'' London Symphony Orchestra (1966, 1965, 1965, 1963 respectively), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6348\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''[[Requiem (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Requiem]]'', Op. 89 (Lorengar, Komlossy, Ilosfalvy, Krause), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SET 416/7\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''Slavonic Dances Nos. 1, 3, 8, 9, 10'', [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6024\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, Symphonic Poems: ''Hussite'', ''My Home'', ''The Noonday Witch'', ''The Water Goblin'', London Symphony Orchestra, (1965, 1965, 1970, 1970 respectively) [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6543\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, ''[[Symphonic Variations (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphonic Variations]]'', London Symphony Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6510\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 1 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 1 in C minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6288\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 2 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 2 in B flat major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6289\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 3 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 3 in E flat major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6290\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 4 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 4 in D minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6257\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 5 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 5 in F major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6273\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 6 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 6 in D major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1965), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6253\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 7 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 7 in D minor]], London Symphony Orchestra (1964), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6115\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 8 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 8 in G major]], London Symphony Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6044\n*Dvo\u0159\u00e1k, [[Symphony No. 9 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|Symphony No. 9 in E minor \"From the New World\"]] London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] S