ano Concerto for the Left Hand (Ravel)|Concerto for the Left Hand]] in D major ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6411\n*[[Ottorino Respighi|Respighi]]\n**''[[Pini di Roma|Pines of Rome]]''\n**''[[Fontane di Roma|Fountains of Rome]]''\n**''The Birds (Gli uccelli)'', London Symphony Orchestra (1968), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6401\n*[[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini]], ''Stabat Mater'' [[Pilar Lorengar]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], [[Yvonne Minton]], Sotin, London Symphony Orchestra (1970/1), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6524\n*[[Dmitri Shostakovich|Shostakovich]], [[Symphony No. 5 (Shostakovich)|Symphony No. 5]] in D minor, Op. 47, [[Orchestre de la Suisse Romande]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6018\n*[[Franz Schubert|Schubert]]\n**[[Symphony No. 1 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 1]] in D major, D. 82, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6552\n**[[Symphony No. 2 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 2]] in B-flat major, D. 125, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6552\n**[[Symphony No. 3 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 3]] in D major, D. 200, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1971), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6553\n**[[Symphony No. 4 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 4]] in C minor, \"Tragic\", D. 417, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6483\n**[[Symphony No. 5 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 5]] in B-flat major, D. 485, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6483\n**[[Symphony No. 6 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 6]] in C major, \"The Little C major\", D. 589, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1970), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6553\n**[[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 8/7]] in B minor, [[Symphony No. 8 (Schubert)|\"Unfinished\"]], D. 759, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL6090\n**[[Symphony No. 9 (Schubert)|Symphony No. 9/7/8]] in C major, \"The Great C major\", D. 944, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6089\n**Overtures ''Des Teufels Lustschloss'', D. 84, in the Italian style in C major, D. 591, ''Fierabras'', D. 796, Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra (1963), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL6090\n*[[Robert Schumann|Schumann]], [[Piano Concerto (Schumann)|Piano Concerto]] in A minor, Op. 54 ([[Julius Katchen|Katchen]]), [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]], [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SMD 1152\n*[[Bed\u0159ich Smetana|Smetana]], ''Bohemian Rhapsody'': ''[[Vltava|The Moldau]]'', ''[[The Bartered Bride]] Overture'', [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] (1962), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6024\n*[[Franz Strauss]], Horn Concerto, Op. 8, ([[Barry Tuckwell]]), London Symphony Orchestra (1966), [[Decca Records|DECCA]] SXL 6285\n*[[Richard Strauss]], Horn Concertos, Nos. 1-2, (Barry Tuckwell), London Symphony Orchestra (1966), Decca BDX1259 \n*[[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]], ''[[Otello]]'', [[Augsburg]] State Opera (1962), OPERA EPK 1220.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Sadie, Stanley. ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', Macmillan, 1980.\n* Jaeger, Stefan. ''Das Atlantisbuch der Dirigenten'', Atlantis Musikbuch-Verlag, 1985.\n* Lyman, Darryl. ''Great Jews in Music'', J. D. Publishers, 1986.\n* Holmes, John L.: ''Conductors. A record collector's guide'', Gollancz Ltd. 1988.\n* Myers, Kurtz. ''Index to record reviews 1984\u20131987'', G.K. Hall, 1989.\n* P\u00e2ris, Alain. ''Dictionnaire des interpretes et de l'interpretation musicale au XX siecle'', Robert Laffont, 1989.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=q33147|label=Istvan Kert\u00e9sz}}\n*[http://www.andreas-praefcke.de/wunderlich/bios/kertesz.htm Fritz Wunderlich Colleagues]\n\n{{LSO principal conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kertesz, Istvan}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Budapest]]\n[[Category:Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Deaths by drowning]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Hungarian musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Israel]]\n[[Category:Accademia Nazionale di Santa Cecilia alumni]]\n[[Category:Franz Liszt Academy of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:London Symphony Orchestra principal conductors]]\n[[Category:20th-century composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Amir.azhieh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Istv%C3%A1n_Kert%C3%A9sz_(conductor)"}
{"title_page": "Chromosphere", "text_new": "{{short description|A layer in the Sun's atmosphere above the photosphere}}\n[[Image:HI6563 fulldisk.jpg|thumb|right|The Sun observed through a telescope with a Hydrogen-alpha filter]]\n\n[[File:The_Solar_Chromosphere_at_the_highest_possible_resolution.png|thumb|right|High-resolution image of the solar chromosphere observed with the [[Swedish Solar Telescope]].]]\n\n[[File:Solar eclips 1999 5.jpg|thumb|right|[[Solar eclipse of August 11, 1999|Total eclipse of 1999]]]]\nThe '''chromosphere''' (literally, \"sphere of color\") is the second of the three main layers in the [[Sun]]'s atmosphere and is roughly 3,000 to 5,000 kilometers deep. Its rosy red color is only apparent during eclipses. The chromosphere sits just above the [[photosphere]] and below the [[solar transition region]]. The layer of the chromosphere atop the photosphere is homogeneous. A forest of hairy-appearing [[Spicule (solar physics)|spicules]] rise from the homogeneous layer, some of which extend 10,000&nbsp;km into the corona above.\n\nThe density of the chromosphere is only 10<sup>\u22124</sup> times that of the [[photosphere]], the layer beneath, and 10<sup>\u22128</sup> times that of the [[atmosphere]] of [[Earth]] at sea level. This makes the chromosphere normally invisible and it can be seen only during a [[total eclipse]], where its reddish color is revealed. The color hues are anywhere between pink and red.<ref name=\"Freedman\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Freedman | first = R. A.\n | last2 = Kaufmann III | first2 = W. J.\n | year = 2008\n | title = Universe\n | url = https://archive.org/details/universe0008edfree | url-access = registration | publisher = [[W. H. Freeman and Company|W. H. Freeman and Co.]]\n | location = New York, USA\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/universe0008edfree/page/762 762]\n | isbn = 978-0-7167-8584-2\n}}</ref>\nWithout special equipment, the chromosphere cannot normally be seen due to the overwhelming brightness of the photosphere beneath.\n\nThe density of the chromosphere decreases with distance from the center of the Sun.  This decreases exponentially from 10<sup>17</sup> particles per cubic centimeter, or approximately {{val|2|e=-4|u=kg/m<sup>3</sup>}} to under {{val|1.6|e=-11|u=kg/m<sup>3</sup>}} at the outer boundary.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | last = Kontar | first = E. P.\n | last2 = Hannah | first2 = I. G.\n | last3 = Mackinnon | first3 = A. L.\n | title = Chromospheric magnetic field and density structure measurements using hard X-rays in a flaring coronal loop\n | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n | volume = 489\n | issue = 3\n | page = L57\n | year = 2008\n | arxiv = 0808.3334\n | bibcode = 2008A&A...489L..57K\n | doi = 10.1051/0004-6361:200810719\n}}</ref>  The temperature decreases from the inner boundary at about 6,000&nbsp;K<ref name=\"nasa\">\n {{cite web\n | url=https://history.nasa.gov/SP-402/p2.htm\n | title=SP-402 A New Sun: The Solar Results From Skylab\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041118125616/https://history.nasa.gov/SP-402/p2.htm |archivedate=2004-11-18}}</ref> to a minimum of approximately 3,800&nbsp;K,<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Avrett | first = E. H.\n | title = The Solar Temperature Minimum and Chromosphere\n | journal = [[ASP Conference Series]]\n | volume = 286 | page = 419\n | year = 2003\n | bibcode=2003ASPC..286..419A\n | isbn = 978-1-58381-129-0\n}}</ref> before increasing to upwards of 35,000&nbsp;K<ref name=\"nasa\" /> at the outer boundary with the [[Solar transition region|transition layer]] of the [[solar corona|corona]].\n\nChromospheres have been observed also in stars other than the Sun.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url= http://solarscience.msfc.nasa.gov/chromos.shtml\n |title=The Chromosphere\n}}</ref> The Sun's chromosphere has been hard to examine and decipher, although observations continue with the help of the electromagnetic spectrum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jess|first=D.B|last2=Morton|first2=RJ|last3=Verth|first3=G|last4=Fedun|first4=V|last5=Grant|first5=S.T.D|last6=Gigiozis|first6=I.|date=July 2015|title=Multiwavelength Studies of MHD Waves in the Solar Chromosphere.|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=190|issue=1\u20134|pages=103\u2013161|arxiv=1503.01769|bibcode=2015SSRv..190..103J|doi=10.1007/s11214-015-0141-3}}</ref>\n\n==Comparing chromosphere and photosphere==\nWhilst the [[photosphere]] has an [[Spectral lines#Types of line spectra|absorption line]] spectrum, the chromosphere's [[spectrum]] is dominated by [[Spectral lines#Types of line spectra|emission lines]]. In particular, one of its strongest [[Spectral lines|lines]] is the ''H''<sub>\u03b1</sub> at a [[wavelength]] of 656.3&nbsp;nm; this line is emitted by a [[hydrogen atom]] whenever its [[electron]] makes a transition from the ''n''=3 to the ''n''=2 [[energy level]]. A [[wavelength]] of 656.3&nbsp;nm is in the red part of the [[spectrum]], which causes the chromosphere to have its characteristic reddish colour.\n\nBy analysing the [[spectrum]] of the chromosphere, it was found that the [[temperature]] of this layer of the [[Sun|solar]] atmosphere increases with increasing height in the chromosphere itself. The temperature at the top of [[photosphere]] is only about 4,400&nbsp;K, while at the top of chromosphere, some 2,000&nbsp;km higher, it reaches 25,000&nbsp;K.<ref name=\"Freedman\" /><ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nasa.gov/worldbolok/sun_worldbook.html\n |title=World Book at NASA \u2013 Sun\n}}{{dead link|date=May 2012}}</ref> This is however the opposite of what we find in the [[photosphere]], where the [[temperature]] drops with increasing height.\nIt is not yet fully understood what phenomenon causes the [[temperature]] of the chromosphere to paradoxically increase further from the [[Sun]]'s interior. However, it seems likely to be explained, partially or totally, by [[magnetic reconnection]].\n\n==Features==\nMany interesting phenomena can be observed in the chromosphere, which is very complex and dynamic:\n* Filaments (and prominences, which are filaments viewed from the side) underlie many [[coronal mass ejection]]s and hence are important to the prediction of [[space weather]]. ''[[Solar prominence]]s'' rise up through the chromosphere from the photosphere, sometimes reaching altitudes of 150,000&nbsp;km. These gigantic plumes of gas are the most spectacular of solar phenomena, aside from the less frequent [[solar flare]]s.\n* The most common feature is the presence of [[Spicule (solar physics)|spicule]]s, long thin fingers of luminous gas which appear like the blades of a huge field of fiery [[Poaceae|grass]] growing upwards from the photosphere below. Spicules rise to the top of the chromosphere and then sink back down again over the course of about 10 minutes. Similarly, there are horizontal wisps of gas called ''fibrils'', which last about twice as long as spicules.\n* Images taken in typical chromospheric lines show the presence of brighter cells, usually called as ''network'', while the surrounding darker regions are named ''internetwork''. They look similar to [[granule (solar physics)|granules]] commonly observed on the [[photosphere]] due to the heat [[convection]]. \n* Periodic oscillations have been found since the first observations with the instrument SUMER on board [[Solar and Heliospheric Observatory|SOHO]] with a frequency from 3 mHz to 10 mHz, corresponding to a characteristic periodic time of three minutes.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Carlsson, M. |author2=Judge, P. |author3=Wilhelm, K. |title= SUMER Observations Confirm the Dynamic Nature of the Quiet Solar Outer Atmosphere: The Internetwork Chromosphere | journal= The Astrophysical Journal| year= 1997 | volume= 486|issue=1 |page= L63 | bibcode = 1997ApJ...486L..63C | doi = 10.1086/310836 |arxiv = astro-ph/9706226 }}</ref> Oscillations of the radial component of the plasma velocity are typical of the high chromosphere. Now we know that the photospheric granulation pattern has usually no oscillations above 20 mHz while higher frequency waves (100 mHz or a 10 s period) were detected in the solar atmosphere (at temperatures typical of the transition region and corona) by [[TRACE]].<ref>{{cite journal | author= De Forest, C.E. | title= High-Frequency Waves Detected in the Solar Atmosphere | journal= The Astrophysical Journal | year= 2004 | volume= 617| issue= 1 | page= L89 | bibcode=2004ApJ...617L..89D | doi=10.1086/427181 }}</ref>\n* ''Cool loops'' can be seen at the border of the solar disk. They are different from prominences because they look as concentric arches with maximum temperature of the order 0.1 MK (too low to be considered coronal features). These cool loops show an intense variability: they appear and disappear in some UV lines in a time less than an hour, or they rapidly expand in 10\u201320 minutes. Foukal <ref>{{cite journal |author= Foukal, P.V. |title= The pressure and energy balance of the cool corona over sunspots |journal= The Astrophysical Journal |year= 1976 |volume= 210 |page= 575 |bibcode=1976ApJ...210..575F |doi=10.1086/154862 }}</ref> studied these cool loops in detail from the observations taken with the EUV spectrometer on [[Skylab]] in 1976. Otherwise, when the plasma temperature of these loops becomes coronal (above 1 MK), these features appear more stable and evolve on longer times.\nSee the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160205135129/http://atkinsopht.com/ast/astrpage.htm flash spectrum] of the solar chromosphere (Eclipse of March 7, 1970).\n\n==On other stars==\nA spectroscopic measure of chromospheric activity on other stars is the Mount Wilson '''S-index'''.<ref>[http://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms11058#t3 ''Observational evidence for enhanced magnetic activity of superflare stars'']</ref>\n<ref>[https://habitability.univie.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/k_habconf2016/pdf/poster/Mengel.pdf ''A small survey of the magnetic fields of planet-hosting stars''] gives \"Wright J. T., Marcy G. W., Butler R. P., Vogt S. S., 2004, ApJS, 152, 261\" as a ref for s-index.</ref>\nSee also [[Superflare#Spectroscopic observations of superflare stars]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Plage (astronomy)]]\n*[[Orders of magnitude (density)]]\n*[[Moreton wave]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alienworlds.southwales.ac.uk/sunStructure.html#/transitionregion Animated explanation of the Chromosphere (and Transition Region) ] (University of South Wales).\n* [http://alienworlds.soutuphwales.ac.uk/sunStructure.html#/transitiontemp Animated explanation of the temperature of the Chromosphere (and Transition Region)]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (University of South Wales).\n\n{{The Sun}}\n{{Star}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sun]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A layer in the Sun's atmosphere above the photosphere}}\n[[Image:HI6563 fulldisk.jpg|thumb|right|The Sun observed through a telescope with a Hydrogen-alpha filter]]\n\n[[File:The_Solar_Chromosphere_at_the_highest_possible_resolution.png|thumb|right|High-resolution image of the solar chromosphere observed with the [[Swedish Solar Telescope]].]]\n\n\n[[File:Solar eclips 1999 5.jpg|thumb|right|[[Solar eclipse of August 11, 1999|Total eclipse of 1999]]]]\nThe '''chromosphere''' (literally, \"sphere of color\") is the second of the three main layers in the [[Sun]]'s atmosphere and is roughly 3,000 to 5,000 kilometers deep. Its rosy red color is only apparent during eclipses. The chromosphere sits just above the [[photosphere]] and below the [[solar transition region]]. The layer of the chromosphere atop the photosphere is homogeneous. A forest of hairy-appearing [[Spicule (solar physics)|spicules]] rise from the homogeneous layer, some of which extend 10,000&nbsp;km into the corona above.\n\nThe density of the chromosphere is only 10<sup>\u22124</sup> times that of the [[photosphere]], the layer beneath, and 10<sup>\u22128</sup> times that of the [[atmosphere]] of [[Earth]] at sea level. This makes the chromosphere normally invisible and it can be seen only during a [[total eclipse]], where its reddish color is revealed. The color hues are anywhere between pink and red.<ref name=\"Freedman\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Freedman | first = R. A.\n | last2 = Kaufmann III | first2 = W. J.\n | year = 2008\n | title = Universe\n | url = https://archive.org/details/universe0008edfree | url-access = registration | publisher = [[W. H. Freeman and Company|W. H. Freeman and Co.]]\n | location = New York, USA\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/universe0008edfree/page/762 762]\n | isbn = 978-0-7167-8584-2\n}}</ref>\nWithout special equipment, the chromosphere cannot normally be seen due to the overwhelming brightness of the photosphere beneath.\n\nThe density of the chromosphere decreases with distance from the center of the Sun.  This decreases exponentially from 10<sup>17</sup> particles per cubic centimeter, or approximately {{val|2|e=-4|u=kg/m<sup>3</sup>}} to under {{val|1.6|e=-11|u=kg/m<sup>3</sup>}} at the outer boundary.<ref>\n{{Citation\n | last = Kontar | first = E. P.\n | last2 = Hannah | first2 = I. G.\n | last3 = Mackinnon | first3 = A. L.\n | title = Chromospheric magnetic field and density structure measurements using hard X-rays in a flaring coronal loop\n | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n | volume = 489\n | issue = 3\n | page = L57\n | year = 2008\n | arxiv = 0808.3334\n | bibcode = 2008A&A...489L..57K\n | doi = 10.1051/0004-6361:200810719\n}}</ref>  The temperature decreases from the inner boundary at about 6,000&nbsp;K<ref name=\"nasa\">\n {{cite web\n | url=https://history.nasa.gov/SP-402/p2.htm\n | title=SP-402 A New Sun: The Solar Results From Skylab\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041118125616/https://history.nasa.gov/SP-402/p2.htm |archivedate=2004-11-18}}</ref> to a minimum of approximately 3,800&nbsp;K,<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Avrett | first = E. H.\n | title = The Solar Temperature Minimum and Chromosphere\n | journal = [[ASP Conference Series]]\n | volume = 286 | page = 419\n | year = 2003\n | bibcode=2003ASPC..286..419A\n | isbn = 978-1-58381-129-0\n}}</ref> before increasing to upwards of 35,000&nbsp;K<ref name=\"nasa\" /> at the outer boundary with the [[Solar transition region|transition layer]] of the [[corona]].\n\nChromospheres have been observed also in stars other than the Sun.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url= http://solarscience.msfc.nasa.gov/chromos.shtml\n |title=The Chromosphere\n}}</ref> The Sun's chromosphere has been hard to examine and decipher, although observations continue with the help of the electromagnetic spectrum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jess|first=D.B|last2=Morton|first2=RJ|last3=Verth|first3=G|last4=Fedun|first4=V|last5=Grant|first5=S.T.D|last6=Gigiozis|first6=I.|date=July 2015|title=Multiwavelength Studies of MHD Waves in the Solar Chromosphere.|journal=Space Science Reviews|volume=190|issue=1\u20134|pages=103\u2013161|arxiv=1503.01769|bibcode=2015SSRv..190..103J|doi=10.1007/s11214-015-0141-3}}</ref>\n\n==Comparing chromosphere and photosphere==\nWhilst the [[photosphere]] has an [[Spectral lines#Types of line spectra|absorption line]] spectrum, the chromosphere's [[spectrum]] is dominated by [[Spectral lines#Types of line spectra|emission lines]]. In particular, one of its strongest [[Spectral lines|lines]] is the ''H''<sub>\u03b1</sub> at a [[wavelength]] of 656.3&nbsp;nm; this line is emitted by a [[hydrogen atom]] whenever its [[electron]] makes a transition from the ''n''=3 to the ''n''=2 [[energy level]]. A [[wavelength]] of 656.3&nbsp;nm is in the red part of the [[spectrum]], which causes the chromosphere to have its characteristic reddish colour.\n\nBy analysing the [[spectrum]] of the chromosphere, it was found that the [[temperature]] of this layer of the [[Sun|solar]] atmosphere increases with increasing height in the chromosphere itself. The temperature at the top of [[photosphere]] is only about 4,400&nbsp;K, while at the top of chro